body:
This commit removes the hw.instance_choice operation from the HW dialect. HW instance_choice was meant to target from FIRRTL InstanceChoice, but in that case it's also necessary to implement FIRRTL ABI (very specialized macros + headers) in HW dialect, which is far from ideal and very challenging to carry ABI info to HW. Since firrtl.instance_choice is now lowered to implement FIRRTL ABI in LowerFIRRTLToHW we don't need HW instance choice anymore. 

I think one representation that feels acceptable to SV dialect is a module op whose name can be configured by a macro:
```mlir
sv.macro.decl @MacroModuleName
sv.macro.module @Module macro @MacroModuleName(in %a: i1, in %b: i1, out: c)
hw.module @FPGA_Target(..)
hw.module @ASIC_Target(..)
hw.module @Top(..) {
 %c = hw.instance inst @Module (...)
}
emit.file "targets-Top-Platform-FPGA.sv" {
  sv.macro.define @MacroModuleName "{{0}}" (@FPGA_Target)
}
emit.file "targets-Top-Platform-ASIC.sv" {
  sv.macro.define @MacroModuleName "{{0}}" (@ASIC_Target)
}
```
```verilog
module Top(){
  `MacroModuleName inst (..)
}

// ----- "targets-Top-Platform-FPGA.sv"
`define MacroModuleName FPGA_Target

// ----- "targets-Top-Platform-ASIC.sv"
`define MacroModuleName ASIC_Target
```

This operation looks usable at least  for macro replacement IMO. 

